rkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Westmill, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","North Petherton, Somerset Council district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"North Petherton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richardson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Richard   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Ritson  .","Americanized form (and a Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Richardsson</b> or <b>Rikardsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  , <i>Rikard</i>.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Richardsen</b> or Norwegian <b>Rikardsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Richarson","meanings":["English: variant of   Richardson  ."]},{"name":"Richerson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson   or perhaps a patronymic from   Richer  ."]},{"name":"Richard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Richeson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson  , but compare   Richerson  ."]},{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Richardson was born in 1480, in North Petherton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Richardson, was 26 and his mother, Mrs John Richardson, was 24. He married Jane Jones in 1508, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1523, in Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1480–1523":"1480–1523","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1500–1543":"1500–1543","1510–1525":"1510–1525","1512–1542":"1512–1542","1515–1560":"1515–1560","1503–1563":"1503–1563","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1457–Female":"1457–Surnud","1560":"1560","Abt 1510":"umbes 1510","1480":"1480","1503":"1503","1525":"1525","1535":"1535","1512":"1512","1523":"1523","1457":"1457","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1543":"1543","1542":"1542","1563":"1563","1508":"1508","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Westmill, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshi